    "summary": "The invasion of Greece by the Persian king Xerxes I in 480–479 BC was the largest military expedition the ancient world had yet seen, mustering forces from across the Achaemenid Empire's vast territories in a campaign to subjugate the Greek peninsula once and for all. Xerxes spent years preparing the invasion, constructing a bridge of boats across the Hellespont and digging a canal through the Athos peninsula to allow his fleet to avoid the dangerous cape.\n\nThe invasion is best understood as the campaign that encompassed the [[event:1004|Battle of Thermopylae]], [[event:1005|Battle of Salamis]], and ultimately [[event:1006|Battle of Plataea]]. Despite initial successes — the capture and burning of Athens being among the most dramatic — Xerxes's campaign was undone by the strategic naval defeat at Salamis, which severed his supply lines and made the army's position in Greece untenable. The withdrawal of Xerxes with most of his army left a rearguard that was ultimately destroyed at Plataea, ending Persian hopes of European conquest.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Persian_invasion_of_Greece",
